<div style="text-align:center"><div style="font-size:16px">
<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">A man who believed he was fearless had nothing to fear except for his own self-doubt. In lieu of a typical mindset, he reassured himself that nothing, and no one, may ever touch him. Despite this stouthearted manner of thinking—spirited, valiant, and the sort—he refused to accept that fear itself is a necessary evil, a calculated cautiousness determining actions. He was a fool. A fool outwitted by himself. He was a mere phobophobe, a man with a trepidated fear of fearing. How ironic it seemed, a man without panic, alarm, or else, yet still feeling an intense unease as a result of his predicament. He had no idea what to do. Despite this, disquietude stood sternly—an aching reminder in the corner of his apprehensive mind palace, a self-imposed ship of Theseus in his brain. </span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">This “man”, as it so called itself, was simply not capable of sapience. It certainly was man-made, but by no means would a human ever construct a superorganism that was contemporaneously feeling and unfeeling. It could not make sense of itself.</span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">To properly adapt in its environment, the organism had to alter its “genetic code” in its entirety. It melded and stretched into inhumane forms. Mottled flesh and viscera resembling corridors, rooms, and amenities. It learned to camouflage itself by looking like the very thing it was confined in. Its skin stretched and hardened like scraped flesh on warm concrete, eventually fusing with and turning into the structure of the nearby walls. It lost the ability to speak. To hear. To touch. The only semblance of humanity still left inside was its ability to feel things around it. It called itself “Aedificium”.</span> 

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">A symbiotic relationship with a microscopic bacterium allowed it to glow softly in the darkness. This luminescence, though minuscule, eventually grew into something greater; an almost blinding glow obscuring its fleshy appearance, a facade masked by walls of white. The creature learned how to section off parts of its body to act with a separate consciousness—through which the first few attempts were unsuccessful—but eventually resulted in something new: Seers. Though not truly a part of Aedificium, they effectively functioned as, and resembled, human eyes. Or, at least, what it assumed they looked like; though truly not “off” by any means, they lacked that life-like luster that eyes had, almost as if molded out of dried skin and viscera. </span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">Through time, this structure would eventually come to be known as Level 12, which would eventually be discovered and documented in the late 2000’s. When an individual first enters Level 12, they will find themselves on the floor of a small garage bereft of most furnishings and fixtures. A rickety wooden desk stands at the center of the room, with a dim, hanging light bulb positioned above. Behind the desk stands a white-painted paneled door that leads to the level’s inner structure. The interior of Level 12 resembles a modern suburban household, varying in layout, with amenities and furniture strewn throughout; however, it is unclear where such furnishings came from, as they are not attached to the superficial structure. Additionally, the level’s superorganism will often noticeably shift the layout of hallways and rooms when unobserved, with it being theorized that the level does this to emulate non-Euclidean geometry.</span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">Extended stays within Level 12 will cloud one’s vision with a noticeable grain akin to television static, which, though harmless, may be strenuous over time, though the full long-term effects of this have not been properly documented. Television screens throughout the level—which may appear occasionally within the level’s shifting layout—are often powered on, displaying flickering noise. Looking into this static can induce headaches, with nausea, drowsiness, and shortness of breath being reported over long periods of time. The level’s windows show a dark, inaccessible sky outside, which exhibits the same effects as the television screens when directly observed.</span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">Level 12 contains a pervasive phenomenon which affects electrical signals, blocking any signals entering and leaving the level. For reasons not yet known, any form of video/audio recording within the level is blocked, with all recorded media corrupting and turning into unintelligible noise. </span>

<span style='font-family:Merriweather;">Seers are an “entity” (classification is unclear) endemic to Level 12. Commonly seen hiding around corners or under furniture, Seers are docile in most circumstances; however, certain reports indicate that they may turn aggressive when directly viewed or looked at by individuals, though they are not strong enough to inflict bodily harm. </span>

 To-do: Further research on camera/digital video phenomenon. How does it function? Also; properly document entrances and exits.



